Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux TerminalHere's a tiny CLI tool to add an aquarium in your Linux terminal. https://itsfoss.com/asciiquarium/ 6523ffbc030e5e08c7c2b5de Terminal FunSreenath Fri, 03 Nov 2023 03:59:00 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/using-asciiquarium-in-linux.png" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal"><p> There are a bunch of <a href="https://itsfoss.com/funny-linux-commands/">Linux command tools that are more for amusement</a> than serious work. Asciiquarium is one of them.</p><p> It provides a simple aquarium like animation effects in ASCII format for the Linux terminal. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/asciiquarium.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy"></figure><p> Looks interesting? Let&#39;s explore it.</p><h2 id="install-asciiquarium-in-linux"> Install Asciiquarium in Linux</h2><p> If you are using Arch Linux or Fedora, you can install it from your official repositories.</p><p> Fedora users:</p><pre> <code>sudo dnf install asciiquarium</code></pre><p> Arch Linux users:</p><pre> <code>sudo pacman -S asciiquarium</code></pre><p> Asciiquarium is not available in the default repos of Ubuntu. So, you either need to use a prebuilt binary or an external PPA.</p><h3 id="install-asciiquarium-using-ppa"> Install Asciiquarium using PPA</h3><p> First, add the PPA for Asciiquarium.</p><pre> <code>sudo add-apt-repository ppa:ytvwld/asciiquarium sudo apt update</code></pre><p> Now, install the package and its dependencies using:</p><pre> <code>sudo apt install asciiquarium</code></pre><h4 id="remove-ppa"> Remove PPA</h4><p> To remove the Asciiquarium PPA, first remove the package.</p><pre> <code>sudo apt purge asciiquarium sudo apt autoremove</code></pre><p> Now, remove the PPA from your system:</p><pre> <code>sudo add-apt-repository --remove ppa:openshot.developers/ppa sudo apt update</code></pre><h3 id="install-asciiquarium-using-binary"> Install Asciiquarium using Binary</h3><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-red"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 🚧</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> This needs separate Perl modules installed to your system. Also, it will install several Perl related packages to your system. So keep caution. </div></div><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Installing-perl-dependencies.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy" width="1400" height="756" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Installing-perl-dependencies.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/Installing-perl-dependencies.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Installing-perl-dependencies.png 1400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Installing Perl Dependencies</span></figcaption></figure><p> To run the binary, you need the Animation and Curses module from CPAN (Comprehensive Perl Archive Network).</p><p> Install CPAN in Ubuntu using:</p><pre> <code>sudo apt install cpanminus libcurses-perl</code></pre><p> Now, run:</p><pre> <code>cpan Term::Animation</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/animation-module-setup.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy" width="1400" height="596" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/animation-module-setup.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/animation-module-setup.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/animation-module-setup.png 1400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Animation Module</span></figcaption></figure><p> This will ask for some configuration, just accept the defaults. Once both are set up, download the Asciiquarium release.</p><div class="kg-card kg-button-card kg-align-center"> <a href="https://robobunny.com/projects/asciiquarium/html/?ref=itsfoss.com" class="kg-btn kg-btn-accent">Download Asciiquarium</a></div><p> Extract the file. You will get a file called Asciiquarium. Now, make it executable. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/execution-permission-for-asciiquarium.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy" width="1349" height="667" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/execution-permission-for-asciiquarium.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/execution-permission-for-asciiquarium.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/execution-permission-for-asciiquarium.png 1349w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Make Asciiquarium Executable</span></figcaption></figure><p> To do it via command line, open a terminal there and give the file execution permission <a href="https://linuxhandbook.com/chmod-command/?ref=itsfoss.com" rel="noreferrer">using chmod command</a> .</p><pre> <code>chmod +x asciiquarium</code></pre><p> Now, to get the animation, you can run inside that location:</p><pre> <code>./asciiquarium</code></pre><p> Or you can place the file in a <a href="https://itsfoss.com/add-directory-to-path-linux/" rel="noreferrer">location that is in your path</a> .</p><h2 id="using-asciiquarium"> Using Asciiquarium</h2><p> Asciiquarium is a simple program. It does not have any command line options. Once you run <code>asciiquarium</code> , you will get the aquarium animation effect on your terminal. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/asciiquarium.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy" width="1280" height="680" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/asciiquarium.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/asciiquarium.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/asciiquarium.png 1280w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Asciiquarium</span></figcaption></figure><p> A couple of in-program keys are supported.</p><ul><li> <code>r</code> : Repaint the animation</li><li> <code>p</code> : Pause or Play the animation</li><li> <code>q</code> : Quit</li></ul><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-blue"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 📋</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> Also, you can use your Arrow keys to speed up the animation </div></div><div class="kg-card kg-signup-card kg-width-regular " data-lexical-signup-form style="background-color: #0cb0b6; display: none;"><div class="kg-signup-card-content"><div class="kg-signup-card-text "><h2 class="kg-signup-card-heading" style="color: #FFFFFF;"> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">FOSS Weekly Newsletter 📬</span></h2><p class="kg-signup-card-subheading" style="color: #FFFFFF;"> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Read and loved by 24,000 Linux users worldwide</span></p><form class="kg-signup-card-form" data-members-form="signup"><div class="kg-signup-card-fields"><input class="kg-signup-card-input" id="email" data-members-email type="email" required="true" placeholder="Your email"> <button class="kg-signup-card-button kg-style-accent" style="color: #FFFFFF;" type="submit"><span class="kg-signup-card-button-default">订阅</span></button><g stroke-linecap="round" stroke-width="2" fill="currentColor" stroke="none" stroke-linejoin="round" class="nc-icon-wrapper"><g class="nc-loop-dots-4-24-icon-o"><circle 