px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Asciiquarium with lolcat tweaks</span></figcaption></figure><p> This will give you various color effects.</p><p> You can use the <code>-i</code> option of lolcat, to invert the colors:</p><pre> <code>asciiquarium | lolcat -i -p 200</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/inverted.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy" width="1280" height="680" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/inverted.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/inverted.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/inverted.png 1280w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Inverted Colors</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="bonus-xfishtank-your-desktop-becomes-the-tank"> Bonus: XFishTank (your desktop becomes the tank)</h2><p> Another similar fun command is xfishtank. It creates an aquarium on your root window, that is the desktop. You can install it from the official repositories of Ubuntu.</p><pre> <code>sudo apt install xfishtank</code></pre><p> Once installed, use:</p><pre> <code>xfishtank</code></pre><p> There are several options which will help you to manage the number of fishes, bubbles etc. <a href="https://itsfoss.com/linux-man-page-guide/" rel="noreferrer">Use the man page</a> of the command to learn more about it.</p><pre> <code>xfishtank -b 100 -f 15</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/xfishtank.png" class="kg-image" alt="Using Asciiquarium for Aquarium Like Animation Effects in Linux Terminal" loading="lazy" width="1506" height="553" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/xfishtank.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/xfishtank.png 1000w,